\@writefile{lof}{\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {2}{\ignorespaces \textbf  {Queueing-theoretic specialisations: M/M/1, Jackson, and cascade.} (\textbf  {A})~M/M/1 specialisation: $TP^{-1}$ on the linear $y$-axis versus utilisation $\rho \in [0.05, 0.95]$ on the linear $x$-axis, $27$ $(\rho , \mu )$ pairs. Navy line is the closed-form $TP^{-1}_{M/M/1} = \rho /\mu $ and amber circles are the universal-law evaluation; maximum absolute residual $2.78 \times 10^{-17}$ (machine precision). This is the empirical content of Proposition~\ref {prop:mm1-spec}: the universal law reduces to M/M/1 under the single-class restriction. (\textbf  {B})~Jackson-network independence: composite $TP^{-1}$ via the universal law on the linear $x$-axis versus the Jackson product-form formula on the linear $y$-axis, $15$ random networks of $N \in \{2, \ldots  , 6\}$ stations with diagonal coupling. Steelblue circles fall exactly on the crimson dashed identity line; maximum absolute residual $2.22 \times 10^{-16}$ (machine precision). This is the empirical content of Proposition~\ref {prop:jackson-spec}. (\textbf  {C})~Cascade serialisation: $TP^{-1}$ on the linear $y$-axis versus cascade depth $k \in \{1, \ldots  , 15\}$ on the linear $x$-axis. Navy circles are the cascade-sum formula $TP^{-1} = \DOTSB \sum@ \slimits@ _i \tau _i g_i$ and amber crosses are the universal-law evaluation under banded coupling; the two curves coincide. This is the empirical content of Proposition~\ref {prop:cascade-spec}: the universal law reduces to pipeline serialisation when coupling is concentrated on neighbours. (\textbf  {D})~Three-dimensional surface of $\log _{10}(W)$ where $W = \rho /(\mu (1-\rho ))$ is the M/M/1 mean wait, over $\rho \in [0.05, 0.95]$, $\mu \in [0.5, 5.0]$, blues colourmap, viewing angle elevation $24^{\circ }$ azimuth $-50^{\circ }$. The steep ridge along $\rho \to 1$ visualises the saturation regime predicted by Theorem~\ref {thm:utl} when $g$ has rank one.}}{9}{figure.caption.4}\protected@file@percent }
\newlabel{fig:utl-panel-2}{{2}{9}{\textbf {Queueing-theoretic specialisations: M/M/1, Jackson, and cascade.} (\textbf {A})~M/M/1 specialisation: $TP^{-1}$ on the linear $y$-axis versus utilisation $\rho \in [0.05, 0.95]$ on the linear $x$-axis, $27$ $(\rho , \mu )$ pairs. Navy line is the closed-form $TP^{-1}_{M/M/1} = \rho /\mu $ and amber circles are the universal-law evaluation; maximum absolute residual $2.78 \times 10^{-17}$ (machine precision). This is the empirical content of Proposition~\ref {prop:mm1-spec}: the universal law reduces to M/M/1 under the single-class restriction. (\textbf {B})~Jackson-network independence: composite $TP^{-1}$ via the universal law on the linear $x$-axis versus the Jackson product-form formula on the linear $y$-axis, $15$ random networks of $N \in \{2, \ldots , 6\}$ stations with diagonal coupling. Steelblue circles fall exactly on the crimson dashed identity line; maximum absolute residual $2.22 \times 10^{-16}$ (machine precision). This is the empirical content of Proposition~\ref {prop:jackson-spec}. (\textbf {C})~Cascade serialisation: $TP^{-1}$ on the linear $y$-axis versus cascade depth $k \in \{1, \ldots , 15\}$ on the linear $x$-axis. Navy circles are the cascade-sum formula $TP^{-1} = \sum _i \tau _i g_i$ and amber crosses are the universal-law evaluation under banded coupling; the two curves coincide. This is the empirical content of Proposition~\ref {prop:cascade-spec}: the universal law reduces to pipeline serialisation when coupling is concentrated on neighbours. (\textbf {D})~Three-dimensional surface of $\log _{10}(W)$ where $W = \rho /(\mu (1-\rho ))$ is the M/M/1 mean wait, over $\rho \in [0.05, 0.95]$, $\mu \in [0.5, 5.0]$, blues colourmap, viewing angle elevation $24^{\circ }$ azimuth $-50^{\circ }$. The steep ridge along $\rho \to 1$ visualises the saturation regime predicted by Theorem~\ref {thm:utl} when $g$ has rank one}{figure.caption.4}{}}
