\@writefile{lof}{\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {3}{\ignorespaces \textbf  {Five operating regimes of the load coordinate $R$.} (\textbf  {A})~Partition of $R \in [0,1]$ on the linear $x$-axis into five regimes: \textsc  {turbulent} ($R < 0.3$, palest blue), \textsc  {aperture-dominated} ($0.3 \leq R < 0.5$, light blue), \textsc  {cascade} ($0.5 \leq R < 0.8$, mid blue), \textsc  {coherent} ($0.8 \leq R < 0.95$, dark blue), and \textsc  {phase-locked} ($R \geq 0.95$, near-black). Boundary values $\{0.3, 0.5, 0.8, 0.95\}$ are marked by dotted vertical lines. This is the empirical content of Theorem~\ref {thm:five-regimes}. (\textbf  {B})~Regime occupancy: bar chart of count of $R$ samples in each regime over $1001$ uniformly spaced $R$-values: turbulent $300$, aperture $200$, cascade $300$, coherent $150$, phase-locked $51$. The widths follow the analytic regime widths $0.3 : 0.2 : 0.3 : 0.15 : 0.05$. (\textbf  {C})~Bifurcation curve $R(K)$ across $50$ coupling values $K \in [0.1, 5.0]$. Navy line is the closed-form $R^* = \sqrt  {1 - K_c/K}$ for $K > K_c$, $R^* = 0$ otherwise; amber circles are simulation; maximum absolute residual $0.0$. The four regime thresholds appear as horizontal dotted lines. This is the empirical content of Theorem~\ref {thm:bifurcation}: $R$ undergoes a pitchfork bifurcation at $K_c$. (\textbf  {D})~Three-dimensional regime cone: phase coherence on the vertical axis as a surface over $R \in [0.05, 0.99]$ and external perturbation $\epsilon \in [0, 0.4]$, blues colourmap, viewing angle elevation $22^{\circ }$ azimuth $-60^{\circ }$. The cone collapses toward zero coherence as $\epsilon $ grows, recovering the perturbed-oscillator response that motivates the regime classification.}}{11}{figure.caption.5}\protected@file@percent }
\newlabel{fig:utl-panel-3}{{3}{11}{\textbf {Five operating regimes of the load coordinate $R$.} (\textbf {A})~Partition of $R \in [0,1]$ on the linear $x$-axis into five regimes: \textsc {turbulent} ($R < 0.3$, palest blue), \textsc {aperture-dominated} ($0.3 \leq R < 0.5$, light blue), \textsc {cascade} ($0.5 \leq R < 0.8$, mid blue), \textsc {coherent} ($0.8 \leq R < 0.95$, dark blue), and \textsc {phase-locked} ($R \geq 0.95$, near-black). Boundary values $\{0.3, 0.5, 0.8, 0.95\}$ are marked by dotted vertical lines. This is the empirical content of Theorem~\ref {thm:five-regimes}. (\textbf {B})~Regime occupancy: bar chart of count of $R$ samples in each regime over $1001$ uniformly spaced $R$-values: turbulent $300$, aperture $200$, cascade $300$, coherent $150$, phase-locked $51$. The widths follow the analytic regime widths $0.3 : 0.2 : 0.3 : 0.15 : 0.05$. (\textbf {C})~Bifurcation curve $R(K)$ across $50$ coupling values $K \in [0.1, 5.0]$. Navy line is the closed-form $R^* = \sqrt {1 - K_c/K}$ for $K > K_c$, $R^* = 0$ otherwise; amber circles are simulation; maximum absolute residual $0.0$. The four regime thresholds appear as horizontal dotted lines. This is the empirical content of Theorem~\ref {thm:bifurcation}: $R$ undergoes a pitchfork bifurcation at $K_c$. (\textbf {D})~Three-dimensional regime cone: phase coherence on the vertical axis as a surface over $R \in [0.05, 0.99]$ and external perturbation $\epsilon \in [0, 0.4]$, blues colourmap, viewing angle elevation $22^{\circ }$ azimuth $-60^{\circ }$. The cone collapses toward zero coherence as $\epsilon $ grows, recovering the perturbed-oscillator response that motivates the regime classification}{figure.caption.5}{}}
